#*
Errors:
Any function from this module, by default (unless otherwise specified), has the following behavioral characteristics:
- if at least one argument of the function is an error, the function returns the error from that argument
- if several arguments of the function are errors, the error from the argument that was passed first is returned
- if an argument is passed to the function whose value causes an error (for example, an argument of an incorrect type),
     but there is another argument with an error, the function returns the error from that argument
- if at least one argument of the function is an error, the function will terminate before any action affecting the application state is performed
- if a function argument has an incorrect type, the function may return an error with code ':invalid_type'
- if a function argument is a function that accepts a number of arguments different from the one specified in the signature, the function may return an error with code ':wrong_num_fn_args'.
- if a function argument is a function and calling the function from the argument returns an error, then the function itself returns that error.
- if a function signature specifies an argument with some method and there is also an argument with type !$'name of the argument with the method', it is implied that their types (.core_type) are equal,
     but the actual type checking is deferred to the method.
- functions are thread-safe

Notations used in type descriptions:
@ustring                   - a string in utf-8 encoding, the type in the real program is 'byte_array'
@sysstr                    - a string obtained from the system encoding, all characters with code \00001a are replaced by two such characters,
     and non-ASCII characters may be replaced by \00001a and the hexadecimal code of the character in Unicode (6 digits), the type in the real program is 'string'.
@type                      - the specified type
(type)                     - instead of type, several types separated by the | symbol can be specified,
     this syntax means that the constant can have one of the specified types,
     if the constant matches the description of several types, it is considered to have the type that was specified first
(types)                    - instead of types, several types separated by the & symbol must be specified,
     this syntax means that the constant matches the description of all specified types
name:type                  - a type assigned a name
$name                      - the type that was assigned a name, if the type describes a set of types, this type can be any of the set
!$name                     - the same as $name, but if the type describes a set of types,
     this type equals the type of the constant used when assigning the name
param(fn:param)            - the same type as the parameter 'param' of the function 'fn'
[container item]           - where container is one of the types: array, box, set or obj; and 'item' is the type of the container's elements.
     If the container is of type array or box:
     Instead of a single type 'item', you can list several types separated by commas.
     This means that the array contains exactly as many elements as the number of types specified, and each element has its corresponding type.
     If only one type is specified, the array consists of a single element of that type.

     If the container is of type set or obj:
     A single 'item' type is specified, meaning the container can contain any number of elements, but all elements must be of that type.
type{min,max}              - in cases where instead of a single type several can be specified (e.g., [container item]),
     this syntax means no fewer than 'min' and no more than 'max' elements of the specified type; if the type 'type' describes a set of types,
     the elements can have different types, but only from the specified set
type{min,}                 - the same as type{min,max}, but without a maximum limit
type{n}                    - the same as type{n,n}
type*                      - the same as type{0,}
type+                      - the same as type{1,}
!type                      - in cases where instead of a single type several can be specified (e.g., [container item]),
     this syntax means that all elements must be of the same type
/type                      - any type except 'type' and error
[table key=value]          - a table in which keys have type 'key' and values have type 'value'
     if the type 'key' or 'value' describes a set of types, keys or values can have different types, but from the specified set
fn(param)result            - a function that takes one argument of type 'param', and the return value has type 'result'
     several argument types can be specified separated by commas, which will mean that the function takes the specified number of arguments of the specified types
     the parameter can be omitted, meaning the function takes no arguments
.name                      - the constant has a method with the specified name
(?constraint)type          - 'type' but only if the constraint 'constraint' holds; if no type results,
     the current signature variant is considered unsuitable
any                        - any type except error
common                     - any type except error, null, box, breaker
nan                        - not a number (float)
inf                        - infinity (float)
-inf                       - minus infinity (float)
$=name                     - the constant from the place where the name 'name' was declared
!!!noreturn                - this notation can be used instead of the function result type and means that the function will never complete its work.
value                      - not a type, but the specifically specified value 'value'

Signatures:
If the documentation lists several function signatures, in cases where several signatures fit certain arguments,
     the one specified first is used.

Additionally:
All functions in this module work with objects as a table that does not have the key :_ (methods), but can still use methods.
If a function description specifies that it works with methods as values, it means that methods are treated as values (i.e., as if it is not an object but a table).
Many functions that work with indexed arrays also work with strings, treating them as an array of characters.
     Whether a given function works with strings can be determined from its signature.
If a function can accept both a string and an array as an argument, but does not treat the string as an array of characters, this is indicated in the function description.
