#@
Comparison of two constants for equality.
If the arguments of the function are not errors, the function does not return an error.
If the function returns 'true', cmp(left, right) must return :equal,
     if the function returns 'false', cmp(left, right) must not return :equal.

signature:
fn (left:null, right:null) false
fn (left:any, right:/!$left) false
fn (left:nan, right:@float) false
fn (left:@float, right:nan) false
fn (left:(0.0|-0.0), right:$left) true
fn (left:.core___equal__, right:any) @bool
fn (left:any, right:!$left) @bool
@#
fn (===)(left, right) null

#@
Retrieving a value by key (for associative arrays and sets) or by index (for indexed arrays).
If the first argument of the function is an associative array and there is no value for the specified key, the function returns 'null'.
If the first argument of the function is a set, the result is taken from the element inside it, not from the second argument of the function.
If 'container' does not have the 'core___get_item__' method, the function works with methods as values.

signature:
fn (string:@string, idx:@int) @char
fn (null, any) null
fn (array:@byte_array, idx:@int) @byte
fn (box:@box, idx:@int) any
fn (table:@table, key:param(hash:arg)) (common|null)
fn (set:@set, key:param(hash:arg)) (!$key|null)
fn (array:@array, idx:@int) common
fn (container:.core___get_item__, key:common) (common|null)
fn (obj:@obj, key:@token) (common|null)

error:
:out_of_bounds - if type(container) == (@string|@byte_array|@box|@array) & key >= len(container)
@#
fn ([])(container, key) null

#@
The function is analogous to the function [], but works with methods as values.
The function is invoked when using the syntax value:token. Example - obj:name
The value 'name' must be known at compile time.
When partially applying the function, 'name' must be specified. obj:_ - access to methods, _:_ - equivalent to fn (obj) obj:_.

signature:
fn (null, any) null
fn (obj:@obj, name:@token) (common|null)
@#
fn (:)(obj, name) null

#@
The function returns 'true' if 'left' > 'right', otherwise 'false'.
Comparison of arrays is performed element by element and stops as soon as one element is not equal to the other.
If the end of one array is reached during comparison, the array with more elements is considered larger.
The function uses the function 'cmp'.

signature:
