#@
If 'arg' is an error, the function returns 'arg', otherwise the function returns [box arg, null].
The function is used to check data that must be in a single instance (box, thread, breaker) for errors.

Erroneous example:
...
let thrd = thread(fn () "hello".println()))
if thrd.error?() // error, because thrd is used later in the program
     fail("error")
else null

let result = thrd.wait()
...

Correct example:
...
let thrd = thread(fn () "hello".println()))
let [box thrd, error] = thrd.uncopyable_error?()
if error.error?()
     fail(error)
else null

let result = thrd.wait()
...

signature:
fn (error:@error) $=error
fn (arg:any) [box $=arg, null]
@#
fn uncopyable_error?(arg) null

