#@
The function combines two arrays into one by applying the function 'func' to their elements and creating a new array with the results of 'func'.
If one of the arguments is an indexed array, the other must also be an indexed array.
If one of the arguments is an associative array, the other must also be an associative array.
The function 'func' is applied to elements with the same indices or keys.
If an element with an index or key exists in one array but not in the other,
     that element is ignored and does not affect the result.
The result type depends on the types of the arguments:
     - if both arrays are indexed, the result type is @array
     - if both arrays are of type @obj, the result type is @obj
     - if both arrays are associative, but one of them is of a type other than @obj, the result type is @table
The function can accept sets as arguments, treating them as associative arrays with the same key and value.
This function treats methods only as methods, so it is assumed that arguments of type @obj do not have the key :_.
The function may use 'func' only for calling.

signature:
fn (array_1:.core_zip, array_2:common, func:fn(item_1:common, item_2:common) common) common
fn (array_1:(@string|@byte_array|@array), array_2:$array_1, func:fn(item_1:common, item_2:common) common) @array
fn (array_1:@obj, array_2:@obj, func:fn(item_1:common, item_2:common) common) @obj
fn (array_1:(@obj|@table|@set), array_2:$array_1, func:fn(item_1:common, item_2:common) common) @table
@#
fn zip(array_1, array_2, func) null

#@
The function is analogous to zip, but for 2 or more arrays.
If one of the arguments is an indexed array, all others must also be indexed arrays.
If one of the arguments is an associative array, all others must also be associative arrays.
The function 'func' is applied to elements with the same indices or keys.
If an element with an index or key exists in one array but not in another,
     that element is ignored and does not affect the result.
The result type depends on the types of the arguments:
     - if all arrays are indexed, the result type is @array
     - if all arrays are of type @obj, the result type is @obj
     - if all arrays are associative, but one of them is of a type other than @obj, the result type is @table
The function can accept sets as arguments, treating them as associative arrays with the same key and value.
This function treats methods only as methods, so it is assumed that arguments of type @obj do not have the key :_.
The function may use 'func' only for calling.

signature:
fn (arrays:[box array_1:.core_zip_n, arrays:common{1,15}], func:fn(items:common{2,16}) common) common
fn (arrays:[box (@string|@byte_array|@array){2,16}], func:fn(items:common{2,16}) common) @array
fn (arrays:[box @obj{2,16}], func:fn(items:common{2,16}) common) @obj
fn (arrays:[box (@obj|@table|@set){2,16}], func:fn(items:common{2,16}) common) @table

error:
:out_of_bounds - if len(arrays) < 2.
@#
fn zip_n(arrays, func) null
